  <h3><i class="mch-compass-2"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-compass-3.jpg" alt="Image of Compass" class="right ppic" />RELATE. Strategies to Enable Effective Implementation</h3>

<p>In this section, reflect on how you can implement this competency in your daily work. To help with this process, review these <strong>five implementation strategies</strong>.</p>
<h3>Tiered Approach</h3>
<p>These implementation strategies follow a <strong>tiered approach of widening circles of influence</strong>. Through this approach, MCH leaders utilize resources and tools to activate change within their organization, which in turn incorporates partners through its systems of influence. Together, changes may be implemented to affect specific target populations and the MCH community in general. </p>
<p><img src="../../images/spheres-of-influence.png" alt="Implementation Model" width="1956" height="700"/></p>
<h3>Implementation Strategies</h3>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-light-bulb"></i> <strong>Self-Reflection Strategy. </strong>How to advance yourself as an MCH leader.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Advance Yourself as an MCH Leader</strong>. Identify your personal strengths and areas of growth by taking 5 minutes to register/log-in to the MCH Navigator's <a href="../../assessment/index.php">Self-Assessment</a> and answer questions related to Competency 4: Critical Thinking.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-book"></i> <strong>Information Strategy. </strong>How to find and use tools to help you.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Find and Use Tools to Help You</strong>.  The <strong>U.S. Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF)</strong> makes recommendations about clinical preventive services and publishes them on the <a href="https://uspreventiveservicestaskforce.org/uspstf/">USPSTF website</a> and/or in a peer-reviewed journal. The Task Force assigns each recommendation a letter grade based on the strength of the evidence and the balance of benefits and harms of a preventive service. Do you know <a href="https://www.uspreventiveservicestaskforce.org/uspstf/about-uspstf/methods-and-processes/grade-definitions">what the USPSTF grades mean</a>? Access the MCH Navigator's Training Brief to learn more about <a href="../../trainings/evidence.php">Identifying and Using Evidence-Based / Informed Resources to Address MCH Issues</a><em>.</em></p>
</div>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-university"></i> <strong>Organizational Strategy. </strong>How to activate your organization.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Activate Your Organization</strong>. Data as evidence are the building blocks of exploration. By understanding data and presenting a persuasive story, decisions about funding, programs and/or services for children and their families can be influenced. Do you and your colleagues want to learn how to make better use of data? Read "<a href="https://online.ewu.edu/degrees/healthcare/masters-public-health/general-concentration/data-analysis-analytics-public-health/">How Data Analysis and Analytics Improves Public Health</a>" to understand how data analytics helps improve patient outcomes and enhances care management. The article explores how public health professionals can use data analytics to help key demographics receive top-quality healthcare and make community members more aware of particular health concerns. Review the key concepts together with your team and discuss how you could apply these approaches in your organization.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-cogs"></i> <strong>Systems Strategy. </strong>How to incorporate partners.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Incorporate Partners</strong>. Simulation techniques place learners in complex situations where there are elements of uncertainty. Working through the situation, usually in a team, learners apply knowledge, deal with issues of incomplete information, problem-solve, and interact with other team members. Debriefing after the simulation and reflection are key components of the technique. Learn how a group of practitioners, administrators, consultants, and researchers employed improvement science principles to accelerate their ability to reach their goals in <a href="https://www.carnegiefoundation.org/blog/lessons-from-paper-airplanes/">Lessons from Paper Airplanes</a>.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-globe"></i> <strong>Community Strategy. </strong>How to engage your communities.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How  to  Engage Your Communities</strong>.  <a href="https://www.countyhealthrankings.org/">Health Rankings and Roadmaps (The Rankings)</a> provides useful information for community health assessment and improvement. Do you know how your county indicator values compare to those in similar &quot;peer&quot; counties, all U.S. counties? Engage your community stakeholders in a conversation about your county's numbers and the health variations they reveal. Follow up with &ldquo;but why?&rdquo; questions.</p></div></div>
	  <div class="evidenceBorder">
	  <h3><i class="mch-bookmarks"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-reflect.jpg" alt="Image of Thought Bubble" class="right ppic" />REFLECT. Staying Motivated</h3>
	  <p>As you work through your growth in this competency, it's important to stay motivated. Here are some tips to help you maintain focus and productivity along the way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Break tasks down</strong>. Break down overwhelming tasks into smaller, more manageable ones. By doing this, you&rsquo;ll&nbsp;feel more motivated to do your work and continue learning. You&rsquo;ll also be less likely to feel discouraged or anxious. Overall, you&rsquo;ll become a far more productive learner.</li>
        <li><strong>Keep a &ldquo;done&rdquo; list</strong>. As you complete the tasks on your list, check them off as &ldquo;done&rdquo;. Keep this list for future reference. Keeping a &ldquo;done&rdquo; list will give you a sense of accomplishment. As such, you&rsquo;ll feel more productive, which will lead to you getting more done in the long run.</li>
        <li><strong>Give yourself a reward</strong>. Give yourself a reward &mdash; even a small one works &mdash; for each task you complete. This serves as a reminder that you&rsquo;re making progress. This will enable you to sustain your focus over the weeks and months.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><img src="../../images/mch-smart-motivation-4.jpeg" width="1024" height="512" alt="Motivational image" /> </p>
